nodes.title: C
nodes.desc: General-purpose programming language developed in the early 1970s, known for its efficiency and control over system resources.

nodes.title: C++
nodes.desc: Extension of C language with object-oriented, generic, and functional features.

nodes.title: Java
nodes.desc: High-level, class-based, object-oriented programming language designed to have as few implementation dependencies as possible.

nodes.title: Python
nodes.desc: High-level, interpreted programming language known for its readability and support for multiple programming paradigms.

nodes.title: Ruby
nodes.desc: Dynamic, open source programming language with a focus on simplicity and productivity.

nodes.title: JavaScript
nodes.desc: Lightweight, interpreted programming language with first-class functions, most well-known as the scripting language for Web pages.

nodes.title: PHP
nodes.desc: Widely-used open source general-purpose scripting language especially suited for web development.

nodes.title: Swift
nodes.desc: Powerful and intuitive programming language for macOS, iOS, watchOS, and tvOS.

nodes.title: Kotlin
nodes.desc: Statically-typed programming language that runs on the Java Virtual Machine and can also be compiled to JavaScript source code.

nodes.title: Scala
nodes.desc: General-purpose programming language providing support for functional programming and a strong static type system.

nodes.title: Go
nodes.desc: Statically typed, compiled programming language designed at Google that is syntactically similar to C.

nodes.title: Rust
nodes.desc: Systems programming language focused on safety, speed, and concurrency.

nodes.title: TypeScript
nodes.desc: Strict syntactical superset of JavaScript that adds optional static typing.

nodes.title: Perl
nodes.desc: Family of two high-level, general-purpose, interpreted, dynamic programming languages.

nodes.title: Haskell
nodes.desc: Standardized, general-purpose purely functional programming language, with non-strict semantics and strong static typing.

nodes.title: Elixir
nodes.desc: Dynamic, functional language designed for building scalable and maintainable applications.

nodes.title: Erlang
nodes.desc: General-purpose, concurrent, functional programming language, as well as a garbage-collected runtime system.

nodes.title: Lua
nodes.desc: Powerful, efficient, lightweight, embeddable scripting language.

nodes.title: Objective-C
nodes.desc: General-purpose, object-oriented programming language that adds Smalltalk-style messaging to the C programming language.

nodes.title: R
nodes.desc: Programming language and free software environment for statistical computing and graphics supported by the R Foundation for Statistical Computing.

nodes.title: MATLAB
nodes.desc: Multi-paradigm numerical computing environment and proprietary programming language developed by MathWorks.

nodes.title: SQL
nodes.desc: Domain-specific language used in programming and designed for managing data held in a relational database management system.

nodes.title: COBOL
nodes.desc: Compiled English-like computer programming language designed for business use.

nodes.title: Fortran
nodes.desc: General-purpose, compiled imperative programming language that is especially suited to numeric computation and scientific computing.

nodes.title: Pascal
nodes.desc: Imperative and procedural programming language designed for teaching programming as a systematic discipline.

nodes.title: Lisp
nodes.desc: Family of programming languages with a long history and a distinctive, fully parenthesized prefix notation.

nodes.title: Scheme
nodes.desc: Dialect of Lisp that stresses conceptual elegance and simplicity.

nodes.title: Common Lisp
nodes.desc: General-purpose, multi-paradigm programming language that is a dialect of the Lisp programming language.

nodes.title: Prolog
nodes.desc: General-purpose logic programming language associated with artificial intelligence and computational linguistics.

nodes.title: F#
nodes.desc: Functional-first programming language that runs on the .NET runtime.

nodes.title: OCaml
nodes.desc: General-purpose programming language with an emphasis on expressiveness and safety.
